04726nam a22005295i 9780804782074DE-B159720200915044058.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200915t20202012cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808047820747 a10.1515/97808047820742doi  a(DE-B1597)564180  a(OCoLC)1198931028  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aPN1998.2 .L376 2012 7aART0000002bisacsh04a791.43/65220944a791.43652209441 aLaSalle, Mick, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Beauty of the Real :bWhat Hollywood Can Learn from Contemporary French Actresses /cMick LaSalle. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2020] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (248 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction: Two Myths -- t1. Teen Rebellion -- t2. The Young Woman Alone: Isabelle Huppert, Isabelle Adjani, and Nathalie Baye -- t3. Juliette Binoche, Emmanuelle Béart, and the Temptations of Vanity -- t4. The Shame of Valeria Bruni Tedeschi -- t5. Sandrine Kiberlain -- t6. Sandrine Bonnaire, Isabelle Huppert, and La Cérémonie -- t7. The Allure of Hollywood -- t8. Alone at Midlife: Nathalie Baye in the Nineties -- t9. The French Meryl Streep -- t10. Agnès Jaoui -- t11. Marriage and Adultery (Same Thing) -- t12. Géraldine Pailhas and Building a Career -- t13. Isabelle Carré and Madness -- t14. Les Femmes d'un Certain Age -- t15. The New Talent -- t16. France and America -- tAppendix One. How to Sell French Films in the United States -- tAppendix Two. How to See French Films in the United States -- tAcknowledgments -- tSources -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aEven as actresses become increasingly marginalized by Hollywood, French cinema is witnessing an explosion of female talent-a Golden Age unlike anything the world has seen since the days of Stanwyck, Hepburn, Davis, and Garbo. In France, the joy of acting is alive and well. Scores of French actresses are doing the best work of their lives in movies tailored to their star images and unique personalities. Yet virtually no one this side of the Atlantic even knows about them. Viewers who feel shortchanged by Hollywood will be thrilled to discover The Beauty of the Real. This book showcases a range of contemporary French actresses to an audience that will know how to appreciate them-an American public hungry for the exact qualities that these women represent. To spend time with them, to admire their flashing intelligence and fearless willingness to depict life as it is lived, gives us what we're looking for in movies but so rarely find: insights into womanhood, meditations on the dark and light aspect's of life's journey, revelations and explorations that move viewers to reflect on their own lives. The stories they bring to the screen leave us feeling renewed and excited about movies again. Based on one-on-one interviews and the viewing of numerous films, Mick LaSalle has put together a fascinating profile of recent generations of French film stars and an overview of their best work. These women's insights and words illuminate his book, which will answer once and for all the two questions Americans most often have about women and the movies: Where did all the great actresses go? And how can I see their movies? Please click here to see a video discussing The Beauty of the Real at the Roxie Film Festival.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aActresseszFrance. 0aMotion picture actors and actresseszFrance. 0aMotion pictures, FrenchzUnited States. 0aWomen in motion pictures. 7aART / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070420440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080478207440